I am trying to sort a list of objects in C++ per distance to an object, as fast as possible.
The problem is, I cannot carry the object's position in the comparer, which is expected to be static:

```cpp
	// Same in List and Vector
	template <class C>
	void sort_custom() {
```

Last time I had to do this for an algorithm I wrote, I added two arguments instead, which allowed me to pass any data structure I wanted to carry for the callback, as if it was a lambda capture (this pointer, some struct etc).

```cpp
typedef bool(*Predicate)(Vector3i pos, void * context);
void some_algorithm(Predicate test, void * context);
```

In this case, sort_custom would looks like this:
```cpp
template <typename T>
typedef bool(*Comparer)(const T & item, void * context);

void sort_custom(Comparer<T> test, void * context);
```

Or alternatively, for header-only code, expect a struct with a `()` operator, nicer because type-safe:
```cpp
struct Comparer {
    bool operator()(int a, int b) {
        // ...
    }
    int some_var;
}

void sort_custom(T comparer);
```

Which is C++03-ish as well, but I don't know how C++11 lambdas can be used in Godot at the moment...
The only workaround I have at the moment is to use a global variable, which is really ugly.

Any ideas?
